{
  "doc_id": "19744",
  "text": "Smith, et al. [CITATION_1] used the psychophysical method to determine MAW when lifting, lowering, or carrying in nonstandard postures such as twisting, lying down, kneeling, squatting, and work with restricted ceiling heights. One hundred subjects (50 men, 50 women) recruited from a college-age population participated in this laboratory study at Texas Tech University. Although this study did not include measurements of MAW in normal lifting (twohanded, symmetric, sagittal-plane) to use as a basis of comparison, the following trends were observed: Ⅲ MAW decreased with increased lift height. Ⅲ MAW decreased with twisting. Ⅲ MAW decreased in one-handed lifts (compared with similar two-handed lifts). Ⅲ MAW decreased during carrying tasks with lower ceiling heights.",
